Azure Service Bus Disaster Recovery Setup Options
1. Geo-Disaster Recovery (GeoDR)
Geo-DR is a metadata-only replication mechanism in Azure Service Bus that enables namespace-level disaster recovery using an alias.
Key Features:
â€¢ âœ… Replicates metadata only (queues, topics, filters, authorization rules)
â€¢ âŒ Does not replicate messages
â€¢ âœ… Allows manual failover to secondary namespace
â€¢ âœ… Uses alias to mask failover behind a consistent name
â€¢ âœ… No code changes needed during failover
â€¢ âš ï¸ One-way replication only; failover is not reversible
â€¢ âš ï¸ Resource-level settings (e.g., RBAC, private endpoints, VNETs) not replicated
â€¢ âœ… GA (Generally Available) feature
â€¢ âŒ Not supported in Standard tier â€” Premium tier only
Pros:
â€¢ Mature and production-ready
â€¢ Fast namespace failover with alias
â€¢ No impact on client connection strings
Cons:
â€¢ No message continuity
â€¢ Requires manual re-pairing post-failover
â€¢ Not suitable for scenarios needing message durability
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
2. Geo-Replication (Preview)
Geo-Replication (in preview) allows entity + message replication across Azure Service Bus namespaces.
 
Key Features:
â€¢ âœ… Replicates both metadata and messages
â€¢ âœ… Supports synchronous or asynchronous replication modes
â€¢ âœ… Reversible failover (both directions)
â€¢ âœ… Clients use same hostname after failover
â€¢ âš ï¸ Currently in preview â€” not recommended for production
â€¢ âŒ No support for private endpoints, auto-scaling, encryption
â€¢ âœ… Designed for low RTO/RPO scenarios
Pros:
â€¢ Full business continuity (metadata + data)
â€¢ Bi-directional failover for high availability
â€¢ Allows zero-data-loss configurations
Cons:
â€¢ Preview-only (as of July 2025)
â€¢ Missing support for several production features
â€¢ Requires Premium tier
â€¢ Complexity in operations and DR planning
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
